50+ Teams from Maryland, Virginia, Pennsylvania, DC, New York, etccompeted at Woodbridge Senior High's Battle at the Bridge. McLean had 14 wrestlers compete, 8 still going in day 2, 5 medals, 2 in the semi-finals and the 126lbs Champion, JACOB DALY! John Drury, Will Lewey took 3rd place, Phillip Davis finished 6th, and Tavian Melvin finishing 8th.

Tied for 3rd with Westfield in the last matches of the night at HWT, Battlefield was in the finals right behind us. JD with a big win in 3/4 match to seal it up as Battlefield finished 2nd and Westfield's HWT finished 7th.

After a few years off, the team returned to Tennessee for the Smoky Mountain Duals. Representing VA competing with teams from TN, KY, WV, FL, AL, GA, and SC with Middle School duals and College Duals happening on both sides. Going 4-2 in our pool, falling to Cabell Midland, WV(59-16) and Johnson Central, KY(49-24) we crossed over in the 5th/6th place match up against Pigeon Forge, TN. (45-24) finishing in 6th in the HS Division.
They did enjoy their first trip to Buc-ees and strolling through downtown Gatlinburg.

The Boys head down to Gatlinburg, TN for the Smoky Mountain Duals
NOVA CLASSIC 2023
nearby_text: Even more of the photos can be found and purchased at the link here ^^^^^

50+ Teams from Maryland, Virginia, Pennsylvania, DC, New York, etccompeted at Woodbridge Senior High's Battle at the Bridge. McLean had 14 wrestlers compete, 8 still going in day 2, 5 medals, 2 in the semi-finals and the 126lbs Champion, JACOB DALY! John Drury, Will Lewey took 3rd place, Phillip Davis finished 6th, and Tavian Melvin finishing 8th.

Tied for 3rd with Westfield in the last matches of the night at HWT, Battlefield was in the finals right behind us. JD with a big win in 3/4 match to seal it up as Battlefield finished 2nd and Westfield's HWT finished 7th.

After a few years off, the team returned to Tennessee for the Smoky Mountain Duals. Representing VA competing with teams from TN, KY, WV, FL, AL, GA, and SC with Middle School duals and College Duals happening on both sides. Going 4-2 in our pool, falling to Cabell Midland, WV(59-16) and Johnson Central, KY(49-24) we crossed over in the 5th/6th place match up against Pigeon Forge, TN. (45-24) finishing in 6th in the HS Division.
They did enjoy their first trip to Buc-ees and strolling through downtown Gatlinburg.

nearby_text: Our McLean Wrestling Family continues to grow... The 2023 version of our Alumni Appreciation Event was well-attended and our group continues to grow. Every Year the
SATURDAY AFTER THANKSGIVING at NOON
we hold our Wrestle-offs, announce our team captains and showcase our past, present and future. We often have alumni come back to compete with current starters, youth wrestling exhibition matches.
Our favorite part
is getting to see the dozens of alumni that continue to return. They may not all be able to stay for the group photo, but we hope you plan to join us again next year!

The McLean Wrestling family hosts another successful Red & Silver Match. This was our annual alumni event where we showcase some of our future highlanders, announce our team captains, the current lineup, wrestle-offs and often some alumni. Great to see the support every year and hope everybody continues to stick around.
Hope to see everybody next year 12-2pm Saturday, November 25th, 2023!

Continuing one of our favorite annual traditions of giving back. McLean Wrestling, along with Phil Chung of Chung & Press, team up to help with the Rise Against Hunger event in McLean where they package 100,000+ meals to help those in need before the season starts.

In his fourth year wrestling on a stacked Varsity lineup, the former Conference Champion and 4 year starter becomes the member of the "Century Club" with 100 varsity victories. We are proud of the former Lions Wrestler, now team Captain. He followed up the celebration with an encouraging speech for his (all underclassmen) teammates. Congratulations to Calvin and the Zug Family all in Ashburn for the event with the chance of it happening today. Cal didn't disappoint as he finished the match in Tech/Pin fashion! The team was hyped!

After the threat of snow, the tournament was shrunk to accommodate a one day event. If you made the quarterfinals; you remained in the tournament. If you've lost just one match; you were all of a sudden eliminated. Even with the tough luck event, the Highlanders brought back 4 medals. 106lb FRESHMAN - Ethan Scurlock (7th), 126lb Junior - Justus Porter (7th), 132lb Junior - Zach Chung (8th), 138lb Senior - Calvin Zug (4th). An overall success and fantastic to see the dozens of alumni that made it back to watch! (Next year, remember to stay for the group photo! )

Oscar Auza defeated brother Roberto Auza after Roberto had a run-in with the trash can. Gavin Legg defeated Forrest Stieg, and Brendan Grammes defeated his 2x state champion brother, Conor Grammes. An overall success and fantastic to see the dozens of alumni that made it back to watch! (Next year, remember to stay for the group photo! )
Delegate Rip Sullivan of McLean presented the 2015-2016 wrestling team with Commendation agreed upon by the House of Delegates and the Senate.

Missing both Shaan Malhotra (113) & 4th seeded Calvin Zug (120) due to illness, riding McLean's 5 finalists, the team earns another 2nd place finish to Whitman HS. Conor Grammes wins his 3rd Grapple at the Brook Championship. Mack McCune and Brendan Grammes each earning their 2nd back-to-back Championship. Gavin Legg falls 1 point short in a regular decision to Whitman HS in the Finals to finish 2nd place. The much awaited return of Cochise Wanzer sees him atop the podium with his 195lb. 1st Place finish. Ethan Guenther also takes home a medal with a strong 3rd place finish after losing only to Roosevelt's 220lb champion, ranked #2 by Washington Post - Chibueze Onwuka.

Gavin Legg falls 1 point short in a regular decision to Whitman HS in the Finals to finish 2nd place. The much awaited return of Cochise Wanzer sees him atop the podium with his 195lb. 1st Place finish. Ethan Guenther also takes home a medal with a strong 3rd place finish after losing only to Roosevelt's 220lb champion, ranked #2 by Washington Post - Chibueze Onwuka.

Highlanders competed in a 16-team Duals event this past weekend going 6-1. Missing starting 126 & 195, they made it to the finals against Patrick Henry (Roanoke) and fell short 39-34. Congrats to Patrick Henry HS!

nearby_headings: Opening Day at the Park - Team Champions
Inaugural Red & Silver Match a huge success!
Conor Grammes - 152lb. 6A State Champion
nearby_text: We had a packed house!
The "Lions" and the "Force" youth wrestling programs were well represented with 5 matches. A barn-burner between the Wanzer twins with a 12-11 finish.

We had 11 matches battled after that. Including a mystery guest that got his "second wind" late in the match, but still falling to Brendan Grammes. And capped it all off with a tough fought 1-0 victory between Conor Grammes and Gavin Legg.
It was great to see all of the alumni and community come out to support the Highlanders' wrestlers. Can't wait to do it again next year!

After a tremendous High School wrestling career, McLean's 2nd state qualifier, Forrest Stieg, had a solid showing going 1-2. Falling one match shy of medaling. McLean Wins 2013 Liberty District Championship!!!!
nearby_text: After going 3-2 at the Virginia AAA State Tournament, Conor Grammes, takes home a medal for placing 7th. The tournament was held in Norfolk, VA at Oscar Smith High School.

After a tremendous High School wrestling career, McLean's 2nd state qualifier, Forrest Stieg, had a solid showing going 1-2. Falling one match shy of medaling. He finished his 4th season with 110 total career victories. He is only the 5th wrestler in McLean High School history to reach such a tremendous feat.

One week after claiming his first Liberty District Championship, Conor Grammes wins his first Northern Region Championship in his first year in High School. Along the way, Grammes did not allow a single point to be scored against him en route to his 45th victory of the season in the Regional Finals.

Forrest Stieg places third at the Northern Region Tournament. Stieg never trailed in a single match throughout the entire tournament. Following an unfortunate circumstance, Forrest was DQ'd in the quarterfinals while leading 12-1. Overcoming the DQ, Stieg wrestled his way through 5 wrestlers to reach 3rd place, and a gain his way to the State Tournament.

Only entering 12 wrestlers into the tournament, the Highlanders put 6 wresters in the finals, taking 4 District Championships, and 2 District Runners-up, along with 4 other placers. The Highlanders' 10 medalists qualify for the Northern Region Tournament.
